<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Git on Mark Holloway</title><link>https://markholloway.com/tags/git/</link><description>Recent content in Git on Mark Holloway</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>Â© Mark Holloway</copyright><lastBuildDate>Sat, 17 Dec 2022 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://markholloway.com/tags/git/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Git notes</title><link>https://markholloway.com/blog/2022/12/17/git-notes/</link><pubDate>Sat, 17 Dec 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://markholloway.com/blog/2022/12/17/git-notes/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="sane-git-pull-configuration"&gt;Sane &lt;code&gt;git pull&lt;/code&gt; configuration&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;git pull&lt;/code&gt; command is a shorthand for &lt;code&gt;git fetch&lt;/code&gt; followed by &lt;code&gt;git merge&lt;/code&gt;. I like to avoid getting local merge commits on &lt;code&gt;git pull&lt;/code&gt;. Therefore I&amp;rsquo;ve add the following to my &lt;code&gt;~/.gitconfig&lt;/code&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code-block-wrapper"&gt;
 &lt;button class="copy-code-button" aria-label="Copy code to clipboard"&gt;
 &lt;svg class="copy-icon" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"&gt;
 &lt;path d="M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2"&gt;&lt;/path&gt;
 &lt;rect x="8" y="2" width="8" height="4" rx="1" ry="1"&gt;&lt;/rect&gt;
 &lt;/svg&gt;
 &lt;svg class="check-icon" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" style="display: none;"&gt;
 &lt;polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"&gt;&lt;/polyline&gt;
 &lt;/svg&gt;
 &lt;/button&gt;&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;pull&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="nv"&gt;ff&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; only&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This will cause &lt;code&gt;git pull&lt;/code&gt; to only do a fast-forward merge, which is what I want 99% of the time. It&amp;rsquo;s the same as running &lt;code&gt;git pull --ff-only&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Graphite notes</title><link>https://markholloway.com/blog/2022/12/17/graphite-notes/</link><pubDate>Sat, 17 Dec 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://markholloway.com/blog/2022/12/17/graphite-notes/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="combos"&gt;Combos&lt;/h2&gt;
